title: For Sale:  Ruger .357 SS SP-101 with Crimson Trace grips
postcontent:
Make: Ruger
Caliber: 357 mag
Type: Revolver
Model: 05719
Grooves/Twist: 5 RH
Turns: 1 in 18.75 "

See photos... gun is in very good condition. Crimson trace grips are sighted in. 

Why am I getting rid of it? 
A.) I am a shooter, not a collector. If I find myself not shooting a gun, I trade or sell. I love my automatics and am just not a revolver guy (Did I mention this gun has not been shot a whole lot?)  
B.) I want to raise money for a SOCOM upper** for my AR to hunt with = a great price for the gun. 

Look on Armslist and you will see $550 is a good price even without the CT laser grips which cost $225 new. 

Comes with speed loader, holster, lock (not shown), orig. box and instruction manual. 

The date of manufacture is 05/06/2009 - spent most of its time since then in the box waiting for an owner who will appreciate and use it. 

**If you happen to have a RRA socom upper you want to take this in trade towards with some cash added from my end... I'd be delighted to chat about a deal as long as the value of my revolver is in line with the asking price or reasonable. (i.e. revolver plus a couple hundred depending on condition etc.)

If you are a reasonable, fair and honest person, you need read no further. 

===================================================

When I first came on Armslist I sold a gun or two and bought a couple with no problems. Beginners luck! At that time I would come across ads with fine print like I am about to write and think... "Wow, what a grumpy attitude."

Since then I have had my time wasted over and over by people who boldly make offers and as soon as they are accepted disappear or begin modifying them. 

You are free to make whatever offer you feel is fair and we can talk about it. But, as a matter of principle, once I agree to an offer, I will not budge an inch. Period. 

Please don't make an offer you don't have the money to cover. I just don't get it. What is the point?

If you offer a fair price and I accept it, don't just assume I would have taken less.  I don't tend to dicker around a lot. 

Please do your research before making an offer. I am not offended when someone contacts me and says, "Hey, I can buy this from www.acmeguns.com (or whatever) for $XXX." Prices vary and recently I found I really was asking too much for a gun given what they currently sell for elsewhere new. I adjusted the price. However, please, please, please make sure the price you quote are for IN STOCK guns. Also make sure you add in transfer, shipping and handling fees if they apply. Anyone can put a cheap price on the tag if they are going to recoup the discount on the way out the door. Just saying... don't get in too big of a rush to say you can get it somewhere else cheaper when you really cannot. 

I prefer FTF deals. I will absorb no part of shipping including my gas. (Plan on adding about $35 to the price)  I will not send until I have money in my hand. No exceptions. If you send a check, it has to clear before I ship. Sorry but that's the deal. 

If you want to offer a trade, send clear pictures of your item(s) to REDACTED  Please understand that my goal in considering a trade will most likely be to obtain something I can get MORE money (MORE than $550) to apply to the purchase of the SOCOM upper.  So don't be offended if I say no to an otherwise "fair" trade, okay? (Why else would I go to the trouble of doing a trade for something I have to re-list etc?

BOTTOM-LINE All I hope for is that folks will be fair and act responsibly. I can promise you this, once I say, text or email the word DEAL ... that's it. I was raised that your word is your bond and I have been offered better deals after accepting an offer and it doesn't turn my head. Once I sold a rifle and then discovered the sight on it was worth over half my asking price by itself. I should have done more research ... my bad... out the door it went. Somethings (like your name or character) are more important than money but hey, not all of us were raised the same and I have plenty of faults of my own. 

Thanks for looking and all the best to you.

Since then I have had my time wasted over and over by people who boldly make offers and as soon as they are accepted disappear or begin modifying them. 

You are free to make whatever offer you feel is fair and we can talk about it. But, as a matter of principle, once I agree to an offer, I will not budge an inch. Period. 

Please don't make an offer you don't have the money to cover. I just don't get it. What is the point?

If you offer a fair price and I accept it, don't just assume I would have taken less. I don't tend to dicker around a lot. 

Please do your research before making an offer. I am not offended when someone contacts me and says, "Hey, I can buy this from www.acmeguns.com (or whatever) for $XXX." Prices vary and recently I found I really was asking too much for a gun given what they currently sell for elsewhere new. I adjusted the price. However, please, please, please make sure the price you quote are for IN STOCK guns. Gun dealers can put any crazy price they want on OUT OF STOCK GUNS! Also make sure you add in transfer, shipping and handling fees if they apply. Anyone can put a cheap price on the tag if they are going to recoup the discount on the way out the door. Just saying... don't get in too big of a rush to say you can get it somewhere else cheaper when you really cannot. 

I prefer FTF deals. I will absorb no part of shipping including my gas. (Plan on adding about $35 to the price) I will not send until I have money in my hand. No exceptions. If you send a check, it has to clear before I ship. Sorry but that's the deal. 

If you want to offer a trade, send clear pictures of your item(s) to REDACTED Please understand that my goal in considering a trade will most likely be to obtain something I can get MORE money (MORE than $550) to apply to the purchase of the SOCOM upper. So don't be offended if I say no to an otherwise "fair" trade, okay? (Why else would I go to the trouble of doing a trade for something I have to re-list etc?

BOTTOM-LINE All I hope for is that folks will be fair and act responsibly. I can promise you this, once I say, text or email the word DEAL ... that's it. I was raised that your word is your bond and I have been offered better deals after accepting an offer and it doesn't turn my head. Once I sold a rifle and then discovered the sight on it was worth over half my asking price by itself. I should have done more research ... my bad... out the door it went. Somethings (like your name or character) are more important than money but hey, not all of us were raised the same and I have plenty of faults of my own. 

Thanks for looking and all the best to you.

CZ 82 in hand-picked select condition from SOG 2 years ago. Finish is 90%, function is perfect, no failures of any kind with more than 300 rounds fired. Chambers the very inexpensive 9mm Makarov round, available even at W#Mart.  About the gun:

It was the military-issued sidearm in Czechoslovak military service in 1983. It is a compact, double-action, semi-automatic pistol with a conventional blowback action. This type of action allows the barrel to remain solidly fixed to the frame, resulting in improved accuracy over pistols with pivoting barrels (like the U.S. M1911 series). The low bore axis of the CZ 82 provides for less muzzle rise and quicker follow-up shots. For added convenience, both the frame-mounted thumb safety and the magazine release are ambidextrous. The vz. 82 was the first service pistol to feature both these features. The bore is chrome plated, which gives it three advantages: longer barrel life, resistance to rust from the use of corrosive ammunition, and ease of cleaning. Another feature of this pistol is the use of polygonal rifling in the barrel bore. This replaces the traditional lands and grooves rifling design with a rounded, smooth polygonal pattern which has a more "hills and valleys" appearance.

I am including the original military leather flap holster, with cleaning rod and lanyard. There is (1) spare magazine in addition to the one in the gun. title: For Sale:  FNX-40 FNH-USA .40 S&W
postcontent:
FNX-40 is a slight redesign of the FNP-40.  They took some of the better features of the larger FNP-45, such as a larger safety/decocker, larger mag-release, and a handful of other internal changes to the older fnp, and called it the fnx.  The mags are, regrettably, not interchangable.  

14+1 capacity, I have 3 mags.  FN has not gotten around to putting Tritium in their sights yet, and no-one makes a tritium night sight for these things yet.  The best I could do is one of the multi-layer light retaining compounds like HK is using.  Not as nice as tritium, but a lot better than the old phospho stuff from the 90's. 

She's in perfect condition, had maybe 200 rounds put through her.  A bit large and hard to carry, though.   Includes a Crossbreed Supertuck IWB holster ($135), and 43 rds. of .40.  I'm a little guy, and while I can conceal it fairly well with the Crossbreed, it gets a bit uncomfortable after about 6 hrs.  

Trigger is better than the HK, maybe not quite as smooth as a good sig P229, but close.  DA/SA with a positive safety/decocker, like the HK type 1 trigger group.  I've never had it jam on me, but an inexperienced friend had consistent problems, so I suspect it's susceptible to limp-wristing.  We would hand it back and forth, without a mag change.  It would jam with him, but never on me, so that's the only thing that makes sense.  All things considered, I trust it myself at the moment, but not to give to my wife.
